social_posts.post_text: Had a wonderful time at the Producers Guild Christmas party! It’s so nice being back for events like this.

I have over 15 years of experience producing, directing, and writing feature films. I have worked as a producer on over 12 film and television projects. One of the most difficult parts of the entire filmmaking process is casting. Casting is difficult not only because of budgetary or scheduling difficulties, but mostly because it can be so extraordinarily trying to ever get an honest answer from the potential actor or their representation. I cannot tell you how many times I have cast an actor after months of belabored conversations with either the agent or manager, and the talent was never even informed of the process.

Obviously, I am not opposed to rigorous and competitive negotiations and clever sales tactics, but more often than not, the casting process is wrought with dishonest and unprofessional dialogue, which leaves the actor never even knowing about employment opportunities. This archaic and unproductive process needs an update and refresh from the ground up.

We strive to create a new human, passionate, and supportive management company that puts our clients first and includes them in the dialogue about their own career on the first point of contact from a prospective opportunity. We also believe that we can work with integrity, authenticity, and compassion for not only our clients but the production companies that will employ them. It is difficult enough to create a film or tv show, and we want to work with the creatives daring to dream large to help make their projects a reality. We love artists and we want to advocate for our clients at the highest possible standard in both care and compassion.

It is no small feat to care for the career and wellbeing of an artistic soul. We want to be the very best in the industry and deliver 5 star service to all we interact with. We need your help, Trusted Investor, to bring our company’s vision to fruition. We believe American Talent Management can be a benefit not only monetarily but culturally to America’s most influential export which is entertainment.

2022 - A Truly Great Year Reflection on New Year's Eve

2022 will stick out in my memory all the days of my life. It was great in many ways, not because of money made or successes achieved, but because it was a year full of many risks, rewards, and memories. 

This was a year full of life lived boldly. It is a year where I regained myself and pursued my passion and calling once again. A year where I discovered new places, spaces, and made new friends. It was a year where my wife and I moved three times and traveled the world. A year where I worked two jobs and started my own company. This was a year to be remembered. 

I remember vividly last New Year's Eve sitting at our favorite restaurant and daring to have hope again that this year could be good. 2020 almost ended me. 2021 I was united to my soulmate but still a very hard year. There were many challenges this year, and at times things were very hard and overwhelming. We literally moved across country twice this year to pursue jobs and opportunities. Now we are back in my home of Hollywood, CA and full of appreciation and gratitude for the way God worked all things out for the good. As He always somehow, someway, seems to do. 

Our New Year's Eve tradition is to write down joint married and family goals, and then personal individual goals. I had a lot of personal goals of fitness, health, vocational, and monetary varieties. I did not achieve all my goals and ambitions. Interestingly, that McKenna and I achieved most of our joint goals. Two really is better than one. This evening we have reservations at our favorite restaurant in Hollywood, Musso & Franks. We have our goals and dreams journal ready to soak in ink. We have our hopes and dreams ready for the new year.

I don't know what 2023 holds, but thank God, I know He holds the future. I am abundantly thankful for everyone along my journey who have encouraged me along the way. Blessings to your New Year and see you next year.

Directing my 5th feature film after a 5 year break.

I directed my first movie “Fortified” when I was 17 years old with some high school friends between my junior and senior year of high school in the middle of summer in 2007. It was such a fun experience. My first film was sort of an experiment to see if I could actually make a full-length feature film I could show in theaters and sell. That movie came out in 2008 and pretty immediately afterwards after my freshmen year of college I made my second feature film “Guilt & Sentence” in the summer of 2009 and then released the movie in the 2010. There was a huge advancement in quality, story, and overall production between the two films, but they were very much amateur and homemade. I loved those first two films and the experiences, but I was eager to improve overall quality and increase the scope and scale of future films. 

Today, February 1st 2023… five years later… I am finally back on set directing a feature film.

We had a fantastic shoot this week. It felt so damn good being back on set and doing what I love most. We had a great day and got 4 scenes shot (big page count). Amazing crew, writing, actors — overall just fantastic. So excited to make the rest of this movie later this year. Please excuse our obviously staged behind the scenes photo ;)

I am so overwhelming thankful for everyone who has encouraged me, taken care of me, loved me, and supported me along the way. It was a tough few years but the Lord is good and brought a lot of wonderful people in my life… most especially my beloved wife @mckennafolmar 
If I were to tag everyone who helped me these past years it would crash the app, you know who you are — thank you! To bosses of various jobs, churches, friends, family, fans, colleagues — thank you.

Oscars® 95 Best Picture Predictions & Rankings

It is Oscars® weekend and this is the biggest awards show in cinematic history! This is the most important ceremony to celebrate the long form visual arts. Film is the most influential and culturally significant medium in today’s worldwide society. 

“Film is incredibly democratic and accessible, it’s probably the best option if you actually want to change the world, not just re-decorate it.”  — Banksy

Whatever movie wins Best Picture Sunday night in Hollywood says a lot about society, buying patterns, film criticism trends, and cultural impact. It is said that the Academy’s awards ceremony can be out of touch with social issues and has lost relevance, but it is still the singularly most important moment each year in cinematic history. Films that win best picture often get a huge boost in sales, some films even re-release in cinemas. Win, lose, or even get nominated — this is the greatest honor for filmmakers.

As a filmmaker myself, I have taken watching and preparing for the ceremony seriously, almost religiously. I attempt to watch all Best Picture nominees (in theaters when possible, or the screeners I receive for various unions and guilds I belong to) so that I can have an educated vote. My family and I watch the ceremony intently as we fill out our voting cards and make a party out of the viewing. 

This year we are ready and can almost see the red (or rather champagne white) carpet from our high-rise apartment building in the heart of Hollywood. 

Here are my best predictions for the 2022 film series of nominated films. The film I believe would be the Best Win for the industry and most reflects audience consumer trends, “Top Gun: Maverick”. But the movie that I predict WILL win is “Everything Everywhere All at Once”.
For Best Director I predict Steven Spielberg for his autobiographical and personal film “The Fablemans”. For Best Actor I predict Brendan Frasier for “The Whale” and for Best Actress I predict Michelle Yeoh for “Everything Everywhere All at Once”.

It was overall a really great year for cinema with a nice selection of artistic and commercial movies.

Old Theaters 
Yesterday I showed McKenna some of my old movie theaters I used to own in Texas. Thankfully she saw my first theatre In Pennsylvania while I still owned and operated the Guthrie, but I had lost these theaters before I ever had a chance to show her these briefly owned cinemas.

To be honest, it was bittersweet. It was sad to see and remember all I lost during the pandemic. We drove for hours to see these places and it felt familiar but also the memories felt very distant and faded. I often wonder if the shutdowns hasn’t happened if I would still own all these old businesses and if I’d still be expanding nationwide. Only God knows, but for some reason He saw it fit to let that whole nightmare take place.

I drove for hours, and reflected on all the amazing things I have in my life because my life took an unexpected nose dive and I found myself ruined financially. That first year was one of the hardest of my life. But now just three years later I have so very much to be thankful for. I have a beautiful wife who loves me and I adore, we have our first child on the way in weeks, we both have careers that fulfill us and we love, and we feel completely at home in Hollywood and are surrounded by friends and our Christian family. 

How did so much good come out of so much bad? That’s God’s plan. Out of the ashes new life is born. Thank you Lord for another day and the bright future ahead. 

I told McKenna about the expression and origin of “burning your ships” how the only way to go forward is to not look back. I’m here for whatever the Lord has in store in the future. It will be good because He is good. I’m ready. Amen.

“THE GREAT SURGEON” (2023)

Happy Halloween (and Reformation Day) from Hard Faith! Here is a metaphorical short film about salvation that Spencer Folmar wrote during seminary at Reformed Theological Seminary back in 2012. This short film has gone through many revisions and updates, but this new version is our favorite and features the voice of Steve Brown! Please share and enjoy. Let us know what you think all the metaphors mean and the theology behind the story!

LOGLINE: “A loving grave yard keeper will not allow the dead to stay buried, and those whom he knows he unburies.”
​
Synopsis: In a grave-world, the Grave Keeper keeps watch over the souls and bodies of those living and dead. Lazarus is chosen to be resurrected into this world and come to grips with the true natures of living and dying. He is given a book, the “Surgeon’s Proof,” which details how to share the same redemption with others.​

PRODUCTION TEAM:
Director & Writer: Spencer T. Folmar
Animator: Maddi Beck
Artistic Director: Kara Brauen
Concept Animation: Andrew Embury
Editors: Amber Shimel & Holly Crumrine

Leaving for 6 weeks for my 6th Feature Film!

My wife and I have been packing for days to prepare to leave our LA home for six weeks to fly across the country to direct my sixth feature film. This trip is unlike any other we have prepared for… because on this trip we have a newborn infant, a dog, six suitcases, camera equipment, on a red-eye flight and then a six hour drive to get to set!

I don’t know how one prepares for a trip like this mentally, emotionally, physically, and spiritually. I guess I will let you know after our first week of filming if we prepared adequately. This is a movie that I first started writing over six years ago. It is the story of a local man who becomes Santa Claus in PA. It is based on the true story of Allen Smith. His story is so incredible that while we are in PA for six weeks I will be spending more than half of that time making a documentary about the real life story.

When we land in Pittsburgh Airport on Sunday morning we will drive across the state and head to set for the week at Bethlehem Pennsylvania. I have never been to this city known as Christmas City USA, but I know there is not a place more appropriate to make an original Christmas movie. Daniel Roebuck is playing the lead role in our film “Saint Nick of Bethlehem” and he is from this charming city in the Lehigh Valley. Danny and his wife Tammy have helped tremendously make this film a reality. I could not have done this movie without them. In fact, Danny and I are going to be co-directing and he has helped with rewrites so much he has become a co-writer and producer!
This has already been a wonderful collaborative experience and I am so thankful to have such a great creative team behind this project. It is our hope that this will be a new classic holiday Christmas movie. We have a wonderful cast and crew. We will be filming all over PA including Bethlehem, Altoona, Philipsburg, & Morrisdale! This will be the beginning of the film shoot with more pickup shots in the Spring.

It has been years since I had the opportunity to make another film back in my home state of PA. I am thankful to have the opportunity to direct two feature films this year and one documentary.

Santa Claus is coming to town! So proud of @spencerfolmar and I just love watching him in his element. It was Margaret’s first time on set and we had the best time ever. Saint Nick of Bethlehem is coming to a theater near you in 2024!

Today is national screenwriters day! Writing has always been one of my favorite activities ever since I was young. What’s so amazing about starting a new screenplay is that you never know where that first page may lead. It could take me to set, editing, to film festivals, premieres, and red carpets. Or the script could be left in a saved folder for years waiting for the right time to produce that film. 
It’s an amazing experience when a film is made and you get to share that story with audiences all over the world. I’ve been blessed to go on this adventure a number of times and always so thankful to bring another story to life. One of my New Year’s resolutions has been to write every day. Whether it’s a few pages or more, it’s been rewarding already. The script I’m currently working on is a very important topic that I hope to make soon. I encourage you to write, it can be one of the most fulfilling journeys of your life.

It’s been three years today since Granny passed away. It feels almost as painful today still grieving her loss. She was the matriarch of our family and influenced us all so much. I look forward to sharing memories and stories of Granny with our little Margaret one day. It’s quite the namesake.

I Think God Might Be Proud of Us

It’s sometimes hard to believe God loves us or even likes us. I fail so much and know my sin so well. The sinless one, the Almighty, the perfect one who created everything from nothing… how could He love or like me? I don’t know. But I hope and have a suspicion that He may be proud of us in spite of everything we put ourselves and others through. 

Despite how much we torture ourselves with our failure and our ongoing sin we somehow still attempt to create beauty. I was struck by this while watching the new Bradley Cooper directed movie from Netflix “Maestro” about the American composer Leonard Bernstein. Despite all the ways the movie depicts how Leonard screwed up his marriage, complicated his work, and robbed himself and others of God’s gift to him, he found his way through it all and still composed beautiful eternal scores and music we hum along to today. 

I like to believe, and had the thought while watching this movie, that God might just be proud of His little sons and daughters made in His image. Maybe not everyday and not in every way, but I think sometimes despite all the ways we fuck up all the blessings we have God looks at us in our struggle and says “Well done, okay and struggling servant”. I mean that’s the words we hope to hear one day in Glory, right? Well done, Good & Faithful servant? I can’t imagine those words being said to me, but perhaps in God’s abundant love and through Grace I may yet hear that praise one day.

So as I look out at this complicated city of Los Angeles, and I see the skyscrapers, the homes, the art, the movies, the symphonies, paintings, parental love, kind stranger, or the random smile of a passerby on the sidewalk… I think God is really glad and proud with how far we have come. We have a long ways to get back home, but despite and in spite of everything we still create beauty and hopefully shine a light to bring others home. 
Amen.
